   "source": [
    "### 1.2 Scaling matrix\n",
    "\n",
    "Scaling is a tranformation that enlarges or diminishes objects by a factor. For scaling in 2D space a factor can be represented as a vector $(x_s, y_s)$ where $x_s$ and $y_s$ are scaling factors for each respective axis (those factors don't have to be equal). On the picture below, V' represents vector V scaled by a factor (0.5, 1) and V'' - by (0.5, 0.5).\n",
    "![Image 2.png](data:image/png;base64,)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "DrOkRTdwj-KO"
   },
   "source": [
    "In this part, you should derive a general form for a scaling matrix and apply scaling by a factor of (1, 0.5) to the vector. First, explain how you derive the scaling matrix:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "2A8_koLXrucV"
   },
   "source": [
    "General form of scaling matrix is a diagonal matrix with scaling factors on positions of vector's entries we want to scale. For example to scale entry $a_{11}$ by factor x we need to put x on position (1,1) of our scaling matrix. It works cause actualy scaling by parameter is one of the elementary row operation. From previous module we know about elementary matrices to perform elementary row operation. General form looks like:\\\n",
    "$$\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "x & 0\\\\\n",
    "0 & y\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix}\\cdot\n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "a\\\\\n",
    "b\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix}\n",
    "$$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "LDNnmozXAyqH"
   },
   "outputs": [
